ial activism, the rise of border conflicts, economic challenges, financial entanglements with foreign powers, and diplomatic relations with India, China, Iran, Saudi Arabia, Afghanistan, and the United States.In addition to ethnic strife in Baluchistan and Karachi, terrorist violence in Pakistan in response to the American-led military intervention in Afghanistan and in the Federally Administered Tribal Areas by means of drones, as well as to Pakistani army operations in the Pashtun area, has reached an unprecedented level. There is a growing consensus among state leaders that the nation's main security threats may come not from India but from its spiraling internal conflicts, though this realization may not sufficiently dissuade the Pakistani army from targeting the country's largest neighbor. This volume is therefore critical to grasping the sophisticated interplay of internal and external forces complicating the country's recent trajectory.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aDiplomatic relations. 0aPolitics and government. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Freedom.2bisacsh1 aAbbas, Hassan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurki, Shahid Javed, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGranger, Serge, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaroon, Sana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJaffrelot, Christophe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJaffrelot, Christophe, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJan, Farah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNaseemullah, Adnan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOldenburg, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/re